        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>No counsel, industrie, or valour sufficient against a Captaine so cunning, craftie, hardie, laborious, &amp; 
                        valiant at aduantage, as Annibal allwaies prooued himself. Till at the last Fortune tooke Scipios part, and made his vertu admirably victorious.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Hannibal"/>
                    <person name="Fortuna"/>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="Annibale" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Annibal, qualis et quantus: etiam hostiu[m] confessione.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Hannibal"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>How remarkable and great Hannibal was, even by admission of his enemies.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Scipio, hostibus quà[m] formidabilis.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>How formidable Scipio was to his enemies.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="hostis fiducia" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Magnifica Scipionis fidutia: diuinum prognosticon Victoria[e].
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Scipio’s splendid confidence: a divine prophesy of victory.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Annibal, priùs Animo victus; quid mirum, si statim Corpore vinceretur? Qualis Animi, Corporisq[ue] vis, talis Fortuna. 
                        Bello forsan vincere potuisset Annibal, callidior, atq[ue] patientior: pra[e]lio vicit animosior: nec tam ideò confidentior, 
                        quia validior, quam ideò validior, quia confidentior. Quod satis est virium, sufficit: ca[e]tera rerum momenta Arte militari, 
                        et Fidutia geruntur.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Hannibal"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Hannibal was first defeated mentally; small wonder that he would be defeated physically at once. 
                Fortune is as good as one's strength of mind and body. A more cunning and unyielding Hannibal could perhaps have won in warfare. 
                In the fight the bolder won, and one is not more confident to the same extent because one is stronger, as one is stronger, 
                because one is more confident. Enough strength suffices: the remaining stages of affairs are dealt with through military skill and 
                confidence.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
